04:21.826 --> 04:25.461
The state has asked, after a lengthy trial,

04:25.463 --> 04:27.829
a death sentence and two appeals,

04:27.831 --> 04:30.832
why we would learn anything new from you.

04:30.834 --> 04:34.803
Dr. Omalu, do you have a medical degree?

04:34.805 --> 04:39.108
Uh, yes. From the University of Nigeria.

04:39.110 --> 04:42.812
At Enugu, Nigeria.

04:42.814 --> 04:44.613
And I did my residency

04:44.615 --> 04:49.719
at Columbia University
Medical School in New York.

04:49.721 --> 04:52.555
Um, I also have master's degrees

04:52.557 --> 04:56.024
in Public Health and Epidemiology.

04:56.026 --> 05:00.562
In addition, I am a
certified physician executive,

05:00.564 --> 05:04.399
uh, with a specialty in Emergency Medicine.

05:04.401 --> 05:06.801
And, of course, I'm board-certified

05:06.803 --> 05:12.108
in Forensic Pathology, Clinical
Pathology and Anatomic Pathology.

05:12.110 --> 05:17.613
Uh, my... My focus is Neuropathology,
the examination of the brain.

05:17.615 --> 05:20.149
- While working as a Medical...
- I'm sorry. So sorry. I'm sorry.

05:20.151 --> 05:24.986
Uh, I'm also completing my MBA
at Carnegie Mellon University.

05:26.824 --> 05:29.625
Oh, uh, and, uh, before I came to America,

05:29.627 --> 05:31.993
a master's degree in the Theory of Music

05:31.995 --> 05:35.032
from the Royal School of Music in London.

05:39.002 --> 05:42.738
Oh, but... Oh, your... Your original
question, uh, what can I add?

05:42.740 --> 05:44.409
Um...

05:45.675 --> 05:50.512
My specialty is the science of death.

05:50.514 --> 05:52.848
I think more about why people die

05:52.850 --> 05:56.054
than I do the way people live.

05:58.990 --> 06:01.623
Hands of the deceased.

06:01.625 --> 06:04.493
Broken and dislodged fingernails.

06:04.495 --> 06:10.200
The hands of a woman who fought
wildly for her life and lost.

06:11.802 --> 06:14.502
The hands of the
defendant, Thomas Chambers.

06:14.504 --> 06:17.072
And that is, in fact,
the blood of the victim.

06:17.074 --> 06:19.774
Now, doesn't that suggest that
the state has the right man?

06:19.776 --> 06:23.779
I thought so, until I heard hour 217

06:23.781 --> 06:25.947
of Mr. Chambers' police interview.

06:25.949 --> 06:30.786
I heard him very clearly
say, "I hate blood.

06:30.788 --> 06:33.122
"I had a tooth pulled as a child once

06:33.124 --> 06:35.690
"and it would not stop bleeding."

06:35.692 --> 06:37.993
- So, I got curious.
- What about?

06:37.995 --> 06:42.063
Hands. I could not reconcile
these conflicting sets of hands.

06:42.065 --> 06:44.065
So, my mind... My mind is... My mind

06:44.067 --> 06:46.034
is going mad, and I'm trying to figure out

06:46.036 --> 06:50.171
if Thomas Chambers' family
has a history of hemophilia.

06:50.173 --> 06:53.074
So, I asked his father
and, uh, his father said no.

06:53.076 --> 06:56.846
But there is a strain of
hemophilia, hemophilia A,

06:56.848 --> 06:59.949
so rare that it is never tested for.

06:59.951 --> 07:02.817
Mr. Chambers tested
positive for hemophilia A.

07:02.819 --> 07:05.687
His hands may have touched the victim,

07:05.689 --> 07:08.791
perhaps to aid her, as he claims.

07:08.793 --> 07:10.793
If his hands had been the murder weapon,

07:10.795 --> 07:12.827
if he had been scratched or bitten,

07:12.829 --> 07:15.197
he would have bled to death.

07:15.199 --> 07:18.968
If the state of Pennsylvania
moves forward to execute,

07:18.970 --> 07:22.673
you will be killing an innocent man.

08:30.774 --> 08:32.342
Way to go, Joe.

08:35.613 --> 08:36.778
Good morning, Gracie.

08:36.780 --> 08:38.214
Good morning, Dr. Omalu.

08:38.216 --> 08:40.715
- Here are the cases for today. Mmm-hmm.
- Okay. This is from yesterday.

08:40.717 --> 08:42.049
Hey, we got a full room today.

08:42.052 --> 08:43.753
- Cycle 'em through.
- Yes.

08:51.361 --> 08:53.797
Let's begin with Rachel Green.

09:18.389 --> 09:22.291
Okay, Rachel, I need your help.

09:22.293 --> 09:25.060
We are in this together.

09:25.062 --> 09:26.628
Please help me find out
what happened to you.

09:26.630 --> 09:28.162
Here we go.

09:28.164 --> 09:29.834
Danny, come on.

09:34.371 --> 09:36.305
Gracie.

09:36.307 --> 09:39.609
Dr. Omalu uses different
stuff. Makes less of a mess.

10:29.092 --> 10:31.225
<i>Possible causal relationship</i>

10:31.227 --> 10:35.730
<i>between self-medication
and early head trauma,</i>

10:35.732 --> 10:37.900
leading to narcotics abuse and overdose.

10:37.902 --> 10:40.268
You're not her shrink, Bennet!

10:40.270 --> 10:43.839
If I know how she lived,
I know why she died.

10:43.841 --> 10:45.840
And you should be careful, Danny.

10:45.842 --> 10:48.478
One day, I may be rushing
through your autopsy.

10:55.452 --> 10:58.921
<i>Dr. Wecht, Dr. Omalu
is here to see you.</i>

10:58.923 --> 11:02.190
You know the reason you're
not back in Nigeria, don't you?

11:02.192 --> 11:04.792
Uh, yes. Because I remind you of you.

11:04.794 --> 11:06.328
Only less handsome.

11:06.330 --> 11:07.932
Sit.

11:09.966 --> 11:12.334
What the hell is going on down there?

11:12.336 --> 11:14.402
Nothing. I'm doing my work. I'm fine.

11:14.404 --> 11:16.037
You're not fine.

11:16.039 --> 11:20.074
Danny hates your guts. I've
never seen anything like it.

11:20.076 --> 11:22.076
I think you're working a little too slow.

11:22.078 --> 11:23.445
I'm a doctor.

11:23.447 --> 11:26.949
The dead are my patients.
I treat them with respect.

11:26.951 --> 11:28.950
But do you have to talk to them?

11:28.952 --> 11:31.052
If you have to do that,
talk to them in your head.

11:32.356 --> 11:35.223
And we discussed the knives.
You're still throwing them away.

11:35.225 --> 11:37.493
We're a public agency in Pittsburgh.

11:37.495 --> 11:40.094
They're expensive. Reuse them.

11:40.096 --> 11:42.964
Would you want me to cut open your mother

11:42.966 --> 11:45.869
with the same knife I
used on a serial killer?

11:49.240 --> 11:50.539
Yes.

11:50.541 --> 11:52.174
I'd probably request it.

11:54.544 --> 11:56.445
Cyril.

11:56.447 --> 11:59.080
You need a girlfriend.

11:59.082 --> 12:01.752
You need to touch somebody
alive every once in a while.

12:02.952 --> 12:05.521
Living women are... Well,
occasionally they're a pain in the ass,

12:05.523 --> 12:07.122
but quite often, they're amazing.

12:07.124 --> 12:08.556
Give it a try.

12:08.558 --> 12:10.057
Okay.

12:10.059 --> 12:12.493
Just be a little less of an artist.

12:12.495 --> 12:15.464
- Fit in a little more.
- Yes.

12:15.466 --> 12:17.997
It's another death row case.

12:17.999 --> 12:19.368
The guy's being railroaded.

12:19.370 --> 12:21.939
$1,000 for you.

12:23.106 --> 12:24.675
Cyril.

12:26.509 --> 12:29.844
Uh...

12:56.874 --> 12:58.940
Webby.

12:58.942 --> 13:00.908
Hey, man.

13:00.910 --> 13:02.945
I am loving the digs.

13:05.182 --> 13:06.949
Mike.

13:06.951 --> 13:08.752
It's Justin.

13:10.321 --> 13:11.453
I'll just sit with you for a minute, huh?

13:11.455 --> 13:13.454
Yeah.

13:22.899 --> 13:25.002
Jugger.

13:26.202 --> 13:29.070
We're all worried about you, man.

13:29.072 --> 13:31.305
What are you doing, Mike? Mike! Mike!

13:31.307 --> 13:33.474
- What are y'all doing? Give me that.
- No, no, no!

13:33.476 --> 13:35.109
It's all right. It's just...

13:35.111 --> 13:37.945
I just...

13:37.947 --> 13:40.449
I don't want to go to sleep.

13:42.186 --> 13:45.052
I heard you sold your
Super Bowl rings, Mike.

13:45.054 --> 13:46.990
Your Super Bowl rings, Mike.

13:53.596 --> 13:56.230
Mike, hey.

13:56.232 --> 13:58.067
Pam's your wife.

13:59.202 --> 14:01.502
- Garrett's your boy.
- Yeah, yeah.

14:05.308 --> 14:07.877
I'm starting to forget things.

14:09.178 --> 14:12.613
I'm saying this crazy crap to my kids.

14:12.615 --> 14:15.585
I nearly pushed Keana into a wall.

14:17.053 --> 14:18.286
I never thought I'd do that to her.

14:18.288 --> 14:19.621
All right, well, don't...

14:19.623 --> 14:21.992
Just don't give up.

14:23.126 --> 14:28.597
All we got to do is finish the game.

14:28.599 --> 14:30.601
We'll all be winners. Okay?

15:24.355 --> 15:26.054
Have a good day. It's good to see you.

15:26.056 --> 15:27.589
Bennet! A moment?

15:27.591 --> 15:30.191
Yes, Father.

15:30.193 --> 15:32.060
- How are you?
- We have a new member.

15:32.062 --> 15:34.396
A young lady from Kenya.

15:34.398 --> 15:37.498
She came to us a couple weeks
ago and she needs our help.

15:37.500 --> 15:38.967
Oh, sure. How much do you need, Father?

15:38.969 --> 15:42.304
She needs shelter, Bennet. Until
we find her something permanent.

15:42.306 --> 15:45.007
Father, I'm working on my MBA.

15:45.009 --> 15:46.507
I'm studying. My books
are all over, everywhere.

15:46.509 --> 15:49.076
She's a nice girl. She's from Nairobi.

15:49.078 --> 15:50.512
Went to British school.

15:50.514 --> 15:52.280
She wants to work.

15:52.282 --> 15:55.117
We're letting her tidy
up around the church.

15:55.119 --> 15:59.220
We're asking you because we know
she'll be safe and cared for.

15:59.222 --> 16:02.089
I feel God in you, Bennet.

16:02.091 --> 16:03.661
Thank you, Father.

16:06.196 --> 16:08.098
Who is she?

16:38.662 --> 16:40.264
So, uh...

16:41.565 --> 16:43.267
You can see.

16:51.174 --> 16:56.046
That is, uh, basically my office, there.

17:03.320 --> 17:05.219
Is that your father?

17:05.221 --> 17:08.556
Ah, yes. The chief.

17:08.558 --> 17:11.159
Um...

17:11.161 --> 17:13.795
Those are my peaches.

17:13.797 --> 17:14.829
They should not be here.

17:16.567 --> 17:18.165
Your room.

17:18.166 --> 17:21.335
Uh, your room. There is a...

17:21.337 --> 17:24.007
The key, I have it for you.

17:25.375 --> 17:27.111
Um...

17:28.310 --> 17:31.246
How are you for... For money?

17:31.248 --> 17:32.983
I have some.

17:36.319 --> 17:38.120
No...

17:38.122 --> 17:41.024
Need is not weak.

17:42.125 --> 17:45.228
Need is need.

17:46.663 --> 17:48.596
I know where you are.

17:48.598 --> 17:50.334
I was you.

17:52.568 --> 17:55.603
You're in America now.

17:55.605 --> 17:59.343
So, you have to be the
best version of yourself.

18:00.477 --> 18:02.177
If you don't know what that is,

18:02.179 --> 18:05.580
you pick something and fake it.

18:05.582 --> 18:07.882
So, I will just...

18:07.884 --> 18:09.817
There, for you.

18:09.819 --> 18:12.153
What did you pick?

18:12.155 --> 18:13.921
- What did I pick?
- To fake.

18:13.923 --> 18:19.227
I picked an older bald-headed white man.

18:19.229 --> 18:21.930
Why an older bald-headed white man?

18:24.268 --> 18:27.371
Because he is the best at what he does.

18:28.771 --> 18:31.141
Do you want to see your room?

18:46.522 --> 18:51.161
I was a registered nurse at the
Aga Khan Hospital in Nairobi.

18:53.363 --> 18:55.630
I understand.

18:55.632 --> 18:58.667
I meant no offense.

19:02.271 --> 19:03.638
Hey!

19:03.640 --> 19:05.606
Hey, wake up!

19:05.608 --> 19:08.343
Hey! Wake up, you.

19:08.345 --> 19:10.679
Come on, now. This ain't no
hotel. You can't sleep here.

19:10.681 --> 19:13.115
Put down your window, let's go!

19:17.587 --> 19:19.821
Wait.

19:19.823 --> 19:21.690
You're Mike Webster, right?

19:21.692 --> 19:24.392
Iron Mike.

19:24.394 --> 19:26.294
<i>I called for him. He's coming.</i>

19:26.296 --> 19:28.265
Okay, but I don't see him.

19:29.432 --> 19:31.632
Oh.

19:31.634 --> 19:33.267
Come on, come on.

19:33.269 --> 19:35.437
Come on, come on.

19:38.442 --> 19:40.574
Oh, what? What is...

19:47.317 --> 19:48.986
Oh, look at that.

19:51.654 --> 19:53.489
Mike, he's here.

19:54.724 --> 19:56.423
Hey, Mike.

19:56.425 --> 19:58.026
- Look, can you, uh...
- Mike, can you hear me?

19:58.028 --> 20:00.728
Uh, yeah, yeah, yeah. You just, uh...

20:00.730 --> 20:03.931
You just have to tell me
what to do, because I am...

20:03.933 --> 20:05.933
I am freaking overwhelmed.

20:05.935 --> 20:07.602
We're gonna get you some help, Mike.

20:07.604 --> 20:09.770
What are you taking right now?

20:09.772 --> 20:11.206
Oh, the Ritalin.

20:11.208 --> 20:13.374
Dexedrine, Prozac, Klonopin,
you're still taking all of those?

20:13.376 --> 20:14.476
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

20:14.478 --> 20:15.744
Come sit down, Mike.

20:15.746 --> 20:17.478
All of it, okay? And superglue.

20:17.480 --> 20:19.546
- Okay.
- Yeah, superglue.

20:19.548 --> 20:22.584
3.5 Haldol. You call his
wife. You tell her he's worse.

20:22.586 --> 20:23.884
He's a lot worse.

20:23.886 --> 20:25.519
You were my doctor. You
were my doctor, right?

20:25.521 --> 20:26.854
I was the team doctor.

20:26.856 --> 20:29.591
Okay! Okay, all right,
then, the team doctor!

20:29.593 --> 20:31.793
All right? The team doctor!

20:31.795 --> 20:33.761
All right? Then why aren't
you helping me, all right?

20:33.763 --> 20:35.896
- I am gonna help you.
- You are not helping me.

20:35.898 --> 20:38.499
You got to fix this! You
got to fix this! All right?

20:38.501 --> 20:40.367
In here, all right?

20:40.369 --> 20:43.938
And in here. I am dying in here!

20:43.940 --> 20:45.472
- I'm dying in here, all right?
- Dr. Bailes.

20:45.474 --> 20:46.908
I hear you, Mike.

20:46.910 --> 20:49.046
It's okay.

20:50.814 --> 20:52.613
Let me give you something
to help you rest, Mike.

20:52.615 --> 20:54.815
You want to rest, don't you?

20:54.817 --> 20:58.753
I just want you to help me, all
right? I just want you to help me.

20:58.755 --> 21:00.020
I will help you, Mike.

21:00.022 --> 21:01.655
Just help me. Just...

21:02.925 --> 21:05.360
- Come and sit down.
- Okay.

21:05.362 --> 21:07.229
Come and sit down.

21:11.934 --> 21:14.035
Well, go ahead, give me the
drugs, give me the drugs.

21:14.037 --> 21:16.403
Show me how you're gonna help me.

21:16.405 --> 21:18.073
- Don't move, Mike.
- Mmm-hmm.

21:18.075 --> 21:20.009
Ow!

21:21.678 --> 21:22.943
Come and sit down, Mike.

21:22.945 --> 21:24.778
Ooh.

21:24.780 --> 21:26.349
Ooh.

21:28.417 --> 21:30.252
- Ooh.
- Come lay down, Mike.

21:34.758 --> 21:37.194
You rest now, Mike.

21:40.797 --> 21:43.064
What am I missing?

21:43.066 --> 21:45.467
- Tumor?
- No.

21:45.469 --> 21:48.036
All of his scans were clean.

22:24.508 --> 22:26.908
<i>Through the years,
the dauntless Webster</i>

22:26.910 --> 22:28.977
<i>had abandoned his
family, slipped into</i>

22:28.979 --> 22:31.712
<i>financial chaos and homelessness.</i>

22:31.714 --> 22:34.915
<i>This is a hard day for the city
of Pittsburgh. On a personal note,</i>

22:34.917 --> 22:36.785
<i>I can remember sitting
down with my father</i>

22:36.787 --> 22:40.054
<i>and him giving me examples
of hard work ethic</i>

22:40.056 --> 22:42.724
<i>and telling me when you get knocked
down, you get back up again.</i>

22:42.726 --> 22:46.594
I'm sorry, uh, I don't usually watch TV.

22:46.596 --> 22:48.763
Then why do you have one?

22:48.765 --> 22:51.601
One has a TV in this country.

23:00.911 --> 23:05.180
Oh, I'm sorry, I don't
usually eat breakfast.

23:05.182 --> 23:08.250
One should eat breakfast in this country.

23:19.462 --> 23:21.830
Dear God,

23:21.832 --> 23:23.565
thank You for the gifts You have

23:23.567 --> 23:25.933
so graciously bestowed upon us.

23:25.935 --> 23:29.504
Please help us to continue to
be deservant of Your blessings.

23:29.506 --> 23:31.206
Amen.

23:31.208 --> 23:32.975
Bennet!

23:32.977 --> 23:35.509
<i>Just hours after he was
rushed to the nearby hospital,</i>

23:35.511 --> 23:37.612
<i>football Hall of Famer,
Iron Mike Webster...</i>

23:37.614 --> 23:38.947
What is going on?

23:38.949 --> 23:40.215
Mike Webster.

23:40.217 --> 23:41.783
Who's Mike Webster?

23:41.785 --> 23:43.218
He's the greatest center
to ever play the game.

23:43.220 --> 23:44.751
He's a true warrior.

23:44.753 --> 23:45.819
Um...

23:45.821 --> 23:47.921
I'm sorry. What is a center?

23:47.923 --> 23:49.524
The big guy in the middle. Hikes it.

23:49.526 --> 23:51.558
My kid plays football because of this guy.

23:51.560 --> 23:53.694
Okay, I'm sorry. I just
did not know who he was.

23:53.696 --> 23:54.895
Well, if you're gonna live in this town,

23:54.897 --> 23:56.898
you gonna work in this town,
football is a good thing.

23:56.900 --> 23:58.932
I freaking can't believe it's you.

23:58.934 --> 24:01.702
Well, as you know, I was put on
the schedule for this weekend.

24:01.704 --> 24:03.705
I am put on the schedule for every weekend.

24:03.707 --> 24:06.710
Come on. Come on.

24:10.579 --> 24:12.980
The whole town was out of work.

24:12.982 --> 24:15.149
He was a guy who gave us hope
when there really was no hope.

24:15.151 --> 24:18.622
Just leave him be.

24:22.592 --> 24:24.726
Look at his teeth.

24:24.728 --> 24:28.598
He was pulling them out and
supergluing them back in.

24:30.634 --> 24:32.901
Gracie, full autopsy, please.

24:32.903 --> 24:35.870
Hey, come on, man. There's no
need to cut this man's body.

24:35.872 --> 24:38.907
Why does an apparently healthy
favorite son of this city

24:38.909 --> 24:42.512
become self-mutilating and homeless at 50?

24:43.747 --> 24:47.215
Cardiac arrest may be
how he died, but not why.

24:47.217 --> 24:48.115
Prepare the body, please.

24:48.117 --> 24:49.752
Yes.

24:55.625 --> 24:58.092
I think what he's saying is that

24:58.094 --> 25:01.763
sometimes in life, you know, you just...

25:01.765 --> 25:04.132
You're asked to leave it alone.

25:04.134 --> 25:06.034
But, uh, sometimes you can't.

25:06.036 --> 25:08.268
Mmm.

25:08.270 --> 25:11.573
Do you believe that he thinks this is
a time that I should leave it alone?

25:11.575 --> 25:14.074
No, I don't.

25:14.076 --> 25:15.309
I never leave it alone.

25:15.311 --> 25:17.746
That's why people hate me.

26:03.159 --> 26:04.794
Mike.

26:06.162 --> 26:10.230
People are saying bad things about you.

26:10.232 --> 26:13.301
I can tell something is wrong.

26:13.303 --> 26:15.937
But I can't do this alone.

26:15.939 --> 26:19.709
I need your help to tell the
world what happened to you.

27:07.257 --> 27:08.858
Hmm.

27:26.009 --> 27:29.443
Oh, uh, sorry. Um...

27:30.814 --> 27:33.948
Regular folds of gray matter.

27:33.950 --> 27:37.017
No obvious contusions.

27:37.019 --> 27:40.789
No shrinkage from Alzheimer's.

27:44.493 --> 27:46.495
What's wrong?

27:49.265 --> 27:52.635
Uh, can you show me the
CT scan again, please?

27:57.807 --> 27:58.940
How old are these?

27:58.942 --> 28:00.807
Mmm, six months.

28:00.809 --> 28:02.746
Six months.

28:17.861 --> 28:20.530
This brain should be a mess.

28:23.298 --> 28:25.634
- But it looks completely normal.
- Mmm.

28:27.836 --> 28:33.474
Records say severe headaches,
double vision, voices in his head.

28:33.476 --> 28:35.776
No documented concussions.

28:35.778 --> 28:37.978
He did complain of dizziness.

28:37.980 --> 28:40.547
- Yes. How often?
- Once.

28:40.549 --> 28:44.518
In 18 years of professional football?

28:44.520 --> 28:46.254
"Joseph Maroon."

28:46.256 --> 28:48.525
Sign the certificate. Sew him up.

28:51.227 --> 28:54.161
Fix the brain, please.

28:54.163 --> 28:57.364
You know we don't have
the budget to do that.

28:57.366 --> 28:59.534
People do not go mad for no reason.

28:59.536 --> 29:00.535
I'm going to continue looking.

29:00.537 --> 29:02.870
No, you're not going to.

29:02.872 --> 29:04.971
Danny, you are out of line.

29:04.973 --> 29:07.275
Hey, you do not speak to me like that!

29:07.277 --> 29:09.242
- I am the pathologist on duty!
- Oh, man.

29:09.244 --> 29:11.112
- I am the pathologist of record!
- Hey! Listen!

29:11.114 --> 29:13.080
This is not your laboratory!

29:13.082 --> 29:15.549
My hands are on this body!
If I am wrong, I am wrong!

29:15.551 --> 29:18.385
- And you are wrong.
- Not you, me!

29:18.387 --> 29:20.587
Fix that brain.

29:20.589 --> 29:23.290
Hey, I am gonna make sure
they don't pay for any of this.

29:23.292 --> 29:26.326
I am going to write my orders
for the tests that I need.

29:26.328 --> 29:27.394
And you're paying for it yourself.

29:27.396 --> 29:28.895
Yes, Danny.

29:28.897 --> 29:31.033
Please, exit my workplace.

29:34.604 --> 29:37.270
Please!

29:37.272 --> 29:40.908
<i>In 25 years, I've never requested
a panel of tests like this.</i>

29:40.910 --> 29:42.476
<i>What are you looking for?</i>

29:42.478 --> 29:47.582
There is not a single
case in a book or in life

29:47.584 --> 29:52.319
where a man that healthy
went that mad that young

29:52.321 --> 29:55.090
with no visible abnormality of the brain.

29:56.925 --> 29:58.926
I don't know what I'm looking for.

29:58.928 --> 30:00.797
I can tell.

30:01.931 --> 30:04.265
It's going to cost you a fortune.

30:04.267 --> 30:06.167
I understand.

30:06.169 --> 30:07.901
Okay.

30:07.903 --> 30:09.937
Well, if you have to play hero,

30:09.939 --> 30:12.508
just make sure we both come out okay.

30:52.414 --> 30:55.917
Dr. Omalu. You got something
today. Left it on your desk.

30:55.919 --> 30:57.450
Oh, thank you.

31:22.545 --> 31:24.147
Prema!

31:25.682 --> 31:28.750
It's very late. Where have you been?

31:32.689 --> 31:35.422
I got a job.

31:35.424 --> 31:37.691
- Look at you.
- Well, uh, a shift.

31:39.328 --> 31:42.330
At a home. Feeding old people.

31:42.332 --> 31:44.968
That is fantastic. Congratulations.

31:46.568 --> 31:49.069
What is that?

31:49.071 --> 31:51.073
Mike Webster.

31:58.315 --> 31:59.546
<i>...phrase is worth $1,000.</i>

31:59.548 --> 32:01.183
<i>And here we go.</i>

32:04.119 --> 32:08.756
Would you like me to get
you a TV for your room?

32:08.758 --> 32:12.593
No. This one will be fine.

32:12.595 --> 32:14.764
Oh, okay.

32:26.375 --> 32:29.209
I can't tell what you're more afraid of.

32:29.211 --> 32:33.613
What you will find, or what you won't.

32:33.615 --> 32:35.117
Hmm.

33:59.769 --> 34:01.804
My God.

34:05.842 --> 34:07.877
My God.

34:32.668 --> 34:33.967
<i>...jacked up from those guys</i>

34:33.969 --> 34:35.768
<i>that are gonna be racing
those sides on this.</i>

34:35.771 --> 34:37.871
<i>Let's get to Jacked Up Number 5.</i>

34:37.873 --> 34:40.708
<i>We're gonna begin with
the Rams and the Chargers.</i>

34:40.710 --> 34:43.610
<i>Mark Bulger gonna be delivering
the ball to Tony Fisher.</i>

34:43.612 --> 34:45.679
<i>Throws it down around his feet.</i>

34:45.681 --> 34:48.614
<i>So, Donnie Edwards is gonna
level him right there.</i>

34:48.617 --> 34:51.351
<i>Always be looking out for
the big hit right there.</i>

34:51.353 --> 34:54.655
<i>- Tony Fisher got jacked up!
- Jacked up!</i>

34:54.657 --> 34:57.557
<i>Number 4, the Seahawks
and the Chiefs.</i>

34:57.559 --> 34:59.760
<i>D.J. Hackett is gonna make the catch</i>

34:59.762 --> 35:02.229
<i>and Ty Law will
launch him backwards.</i>

35:02.231 --> 35:04.699
<i>How far backwards?</i>

35:04.701 --> 35:08.401
<i>Eyes on me! Eyes on me! Gentlemen!</i>

35:08.403 --> 35:11.237
This is a game of awareness.

35:11.239 --> 35:14.641
It is a game of desire. That's why
we have the three-whistle drill.

35:14.643 --> 35:16.510
Let's go!

35:16.512 --> 35:18.646
<i>When I blow this
whistle three times,</i>

35:18.648 --> 35:21.248
<i>you seek out a
teammate. Any teammate.</i>

35:21.250 --> 35:24.684
You make collision, you be
physical, you be violent!

35:24.686 --> 35:26.286
Bring it in here, let's go! Bring it in!

35:29.759 --> 35:32.392
<i>The only way you're gonna get
this player's hands off you,</i>

35:32.394 --> 35:34.561
you grab him by the throat and you squeeze!

35:34.563 --> 35:39.200
You choke him until shit runs
down his leg! Do you understand me?

35:39.202 --> 35:40.202
- Oh!
- Ooh, ooh, wow.

35:50.980 --> 35:52.679
Let's go! Let's go!

35:53.949 --> 35:55.916
Drive! Drive! Hit him!

35:55.918 --> 35:58.851
Hit it! Drive! Drive!

35:58.853 --> 36:01.287
<i>The Jaguars and the
Eagles. Dirk Johnson.</i>

36:01.289 --> 36:03.958
<i>And I'm gonna wait for this
because the look on his face</i>

36:03.960 --> 36:06.293
<i>- tells you that he got jacked up!
- Jacked up!</i>

36:12.434 --> 36:15.235
<i>And our Number 1 hit of the week,</i>

36:15.237 --> 36:17.804
<i>Jon Kitna dropping back the pass,</i>

36:17.806 --> 36:22.709
<i>and Shawntae Spencer
lifts him off his feet!</i>

36:22.711 --> 36:27.149
<i>- Oh, my God! And Jon Kitna got jacked up!
- Jacked up!</i>

36:49.938 --> 36:52.373
You should see this, Bennet.

36:55.577 --> 36:58.979
It's actually really beautiful.

36:58.981 --> 37:01.914
<i>Priest Holmes, he's diving.
Yes, he's got it! Touchdown!</i>

37:01.916 --> 37:04.452
<i>Oh, tremendous! Tremendous catch!</i>

37:07.289 --> 37:09.423
I want to show you something.

37:09.425 --> 37:11.659
A human brain

37:11.661 --> 37:16.299
sits in a fluid completely
disconnected from the human skull.

37:52.668 --> 37:56.238
Bennet, will you relax?
I can hear you breathing.

38:05.681 --> 38:08.451
This is a really terrible brain.

38:10.552 --> 38:12.452
Ever met the great DeKosky before?

38:12.454 --> 38:15.024
Expect two minutes, tops.

38:16.358 --> 38:18.124
Is that him?

38:18.126 --> 38:20.129
So, you're our prize graduate.

38:39.981 --> 38:41.782
Tell him.

38:41.784 --> 38:44.150
It's Mike Webster.

38:44.152 --> 38:45.452
The Pittsburgh...

38:45.454 --> 38:46.987
I know who Mike Webster is.

38:46.989 --> 38:48.454
Steve.

38:48.456 --> 38:50.359
He was 50.

39:05.474 --> 39:07.141
You have my attention.

39:14.483 --> 39:15.883
The Cape gannet.

39:15.885 --> 39:21.188
A diving bird capable of generating
speeds of up to 75 miles per hour,

39:21.190 --> 39:25.261
turning itself into a missile as it
collides with the face of the sea.

39:27.163 --> 39:30.998
The red-head woodpecker can
absorb a G-force of 1,000,

39:31.000 --> 39:34.501
pecking a tree 12,000 times per day,

39:34.503 --> 39:37.440
85 million times over its lifetime.

39:41.443 --> 39:43.577
Bighorn sheep can generate...

39:43.579 --> 39:45.281
- Bennet.
- Hmm?

39:46.614 --> 39:49.350
Okay, okay.

39:50.885 --> 39:54.987
All of these animals have shock
absorbers built into their bodies.

39:54.989 --> 39:56.956
The woodpecker's tongue extends through

39:56.958 --> 39:58.592
the back of the mouth out of the nostril,

39:58.594 --> 40:00.927
encircling the entire cranium.

40:00.929 --> 40:03.530
It is the anatomical equivalent

40:03.532 --> 40:05.865
of a safety belt for its brain.

40:05.867 --> 40:07.867
Human beings?

40:07.869 --> 40:10.838
Not a single piece of our anatomy

40:10.840 --> 40:13.673
protects us from those types of collisions.

40:13.675 --> 40:17.911
A human being will get concussed at 60 G's.

40:17.913 --> 40:22.081
A common head-to-head
contact on a football field?

40:22.083 --> 40:24.652
One hundred G's.

40:26.222 --> 40:29.956
God did not intend for us to play football.

40:29.958 --> 40:33.494
Let's keep God out of this.

40:33.496 --> 40:35.695
Okay.

40:35.697 --> 40:38.166
Um, okay. Look.

40:44.239 --> 40:45.639
What are the S's?

40:45.641 --> 40:47.941
Uh, the Steelers.

40:47.943 --> 40:50.244
- And the O's?
- The others, obviously.

40:50.246 --> 40:51.711
Yes, the other team.

40:51.713 --> 40:53.646
Do you even watch football?

40:53.648 --> 40:55.282
Uh, no, not at all.

40:55.284 --> 40:58.017
But I've been studying
Mike Webster's position.

40:58.019 --> 41:00.686
The man in the middle is quite deceptively

41:00.688 --> 41:02.856
the most violent position on the field.

41:02.858 --> 41:05.157
The slaps, the punches, the forearm.

41:05.159 --> 41:08.729
It is an unremitting storm
of sub-concussive blows.

41:08.731 --> 41:12.733
The head as a weapon on every
single play of every single game

41:12.735 --> 41:14.267
of every single practice, from the time

41:14.269 --> 41:17.271
he was a little boy to a college man,

41:17.273 --> 41:21.541
culminating in an 18-year
professional career.

41:21.543 --> 41:23.276
By my calculations,

41:23.278 --> 41:25.679
Mike Webster sustained

41:25.681 --> 41:29.484
more than 70,000 blows to his head.

41:31.052 --> 41:34.021
Now, now, these men, these men,

41:34.023 --> 41:36.757
these are the fastest.

41:36.759 --> 41:40.726
Now, their speed multiplied by
the speed of the men who hit them,

41:40.728 --> 41:42.896
the G-forces generated

41:42.898 --> 41:47.034
equivalent to hitting them on
the helmet with a sledgehammer.

41:47.036 --> 41:49.235
All of this

41:49.237 --> 41:52.639
triggered a cascading
series of neurological events

41:52.641 --> 41:54.340
which unleashed killer proteins

41:54.342 --> 41:58.177
upon Mike Webster's brain,

41:58.179 --> 42:04.184
the tangles invading and strangling
his mind from the inside out.

42:04.186 --> 42:08.789
Like pouring wet concrete
down kitchen pipes.

42:08.791 --> 42:13.796
As it hardens, it chokes the
brain, leaving him unrecognizable,

42:15.197 --> 42:17.466
even to himself.

42:18.701 --> 42:22.735
I don't know football. I've never played.

42:22.737 --> 42:28.309
But I am telling you that playing
football killed Mike Webster.

42:29.378 --> 42:31.945
And I am certain that there are others.

42:31.947 --> 42:34.313
And how can you possibly know that?

42:34.315 --> 42:36.249
Common sense.

42:36.251 --> 42:38.050
But they are either dead or lost

42:38.052 --> 42:39.820
in the way that Mike Webster was lost.

42:39.822 --> 42:42.188
I'm not interested in common sense.

42:42.190 --> 42:44.324
I'm interested in science.

42:44.326 --> 42:46.659
And science is knowing.

42:46.661 --> 42:49.329
I know from these players' records

42:49.331 --> 42:52.766
that their doctors believe
they have early Alzheimer's,

42:52.768 --> 42:55.334
which is statistically impossible.

42:55.336 --> 42:57.970
They're too young.

42:57.972 --> 43:01.240
Because it's not Alzheimer's.

43:01.242 --> 43:02.877
It is this.

43:24.400 --> 43:26.999
I don't like it.

43:27.001 --> 43:28.434
No.

43:28.436 --> 43:31.438
No, actually, I hate it.

43:31.440 --> 43:33.776
But as a scientist,

43:35.811 --> 43:37.846
I can't deny it.

43:38.880 --> 43:42.317
Name it. You have to give this a name.

44:07.710 --> 44:11.010
Oh, I'm sorry. Did I wake you?

44:11.012 --> 44:14.380
Did they agree what it is?

44:14.382 --> 44:16.450
Oh.

44:16.452 --> 44:20.086
Yes, yes. We are going to publish.

44:20.088 --> 44:21.822
They...

44:21.824 --> 44:24.324
- With you?
- Yes.

44:24.326 --> 44:27.159
In a medical journal.

44:27.161 --> 44:28.795
With you?

44:28.797 --> 44:32.199
Yes, with me. Together.

44:32.201 --> 44:34.435
That's so...

44:36.371 --> 44:39.072
Congratulations.

44:39.074 --> 44:41.410
Thank you. Thank you.

44:44.179 --> 44:46.912
Uh, you, um...

44:46.914 --> 44:49.449
Are you going somewhere?

44:49.451 --> 44:51.383
Yes.

44:51.385 --> 44:53.987
With you.

44:53.989 --> 44:55.421
To celebrate.

45:11.940 --> 45:14.340
You don't dance, do you?

46:56.077 --> 47:00.082
I had quite a revelation tonight.

47:02.650 --> 47:05.918
This body was made for dancing.

47:05.920 --> 47:08.621
When they say "dancing
machine," I am what they mean.

47:10.626 --> 47:13.962
I'm very proud of you.

47:17.632 --> 47:18.999
Okay.

47:43.659 --> 47:46.458
May I kiss you?

48:32.708 --> 48:34.974
- Good morning.
- Cyril.

48:34.976 --> 48:37.978
It's very weird to bring
women into the morgue at night.

48:37.980 --> 48:39.045
She is a friend.

48:39.047 --> 48:41.581
You don't have friends.

48:41.583 --> 48:43.615
Listen, Danny knows she's been in there.

48:43.617 --> 48:45.385
He's thinking about
filing a formal complaint.

48:45.387 --> 48:47.320
What?

48:47.322 --> 48:49.222
I was working on Webster.

48:49.224 --> 48:51.191
I know. I'll take care of it.

48:51.193 --> 48:54.226
How much has that cost you so far?

48:54.228 --> 48:55.295
$20,000.

48:55.297 --> 48:56.729
Twenty?

48:56.731 --> 48:59.032
I save.

48:59.034 --> 49:02.004
- Everything.
- Really? How un-American.

49:03.204 --> 49:05.438
Well, maybe it was worth it.

49:05.440 --> 49:07.307
I got the call.

49:07.309 --> 49:09.775
Chronic traumatic encephalopathy.

49:09.777 --> 49:11.344
Got a nice ring to it, doesn't it?

49:11.346 --> 49:13.213
Yes. CTE.

49:13.215 --> 49:15.215
So, what happens now?

49:15.217 --> 49:19.084
We publish. Uh, DeKosky
is going to coauthor.

49:19.086 --> 49:20.487
- DeKosky?
- Yes.

49:20.489 --> 49:25.624
Omalu, DeKosky and Cyril Wecht.

49:25.626 --> 49:27.194
Oh.

49:28.295 --> 49:30.764
Well, I'm very proud of you.

49:30.766 --> 49:33.199
Thank you.

49:33.201 --> 49:35.367
See? The gray's the right color.

49:35.369 --> 49:37.604
The blue shows the dirt, even in the rain.

49:37.606 --> 49:39.808
Here you go.

49:46.681 --> 49:48.648
Let's go, baby!

49:49.818 --> 49:52.117
Come on, get it, get it, get it!

49:52.119 --> 49:55.487
<i>And watch the play-action.
The safeties jump up.</i>

49:55.489 --> 49:57.389
<i>And look at that touch
by Ben Roethlisberger.</i>

49:57.391 --> 50:00.159
<i>And Plaxico Burress
does a great job.</i>

50:00.161 --> 50:00.793
<i>Looked like he tripped...</i>

50:00.795 --> 50:03.530
You may not!

50:03.532 --> 50:06.766
I say not to, but he does.

50:06.768 --> 50:10.670
<i>Roethlisberger scrambling
out of the pocket.</i>

50:10.672 --> 50:13.072
<i>Throwing across the middle! Caught!</i>

50:13.074 --> 50:15.641
<i>Burress at the 45!</i>

50:17.144 --> 50:19.281
<i>And if you don't know, Plaxico!</i>

50:22.617 --> 50:26.755
<i>Yeah. That was a pressure
toss by the rook.</i>

50:28.722 --> 50:30.789
- I'm hearing voices.
- Are you serious?

50:30.791 --> 50:33.126
- They're just talking.
- Stop. Justin, stop. You're scaring me.

50:33.128 --> 50:34.461
You're scaring them.

50:34.463 --> 50:35.528
Look at me!

50:37.099 --> 50:38.530
They're telling me to kill you.

50:38.532 --> 50:40.733
They're telling me to kill you!

50:43.304 --> 50:45.804
Get out! Get out!

50:45.806 --> 50:47.875
Get out!

50:58.619 --> 50:59.686
No!

51:02.657 --> 51:04.590
No!

51:04.592 --> 51:06.159
<i>All units, black pickup</i>

51:06.161 --> 51:07.561
<i>spotted on thruway eight miles...</i>

51:07.563 --> 51:09.862
<i>Okay, I see him. Just
passing me. Where am I?</i>

51:09.864 --> 51:12.764
<i>Reportedly driving into
